{"audits":[{"idea_id":"9a0072f4cf3a0ff3","agent":"codex","title":"The Custody of Unclaimed Attention","exact_claim":"After object and self-story loosen, traditions differ by where the freed attention is allowed to belong: no owner, witnessing Self, or God.","claim_units":["The practical movement is loosening attention from objects and ordinary self-story.","Udana 1.10 makes the sense fields sufficient and denies any locatable you there.","Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23 makes the unseen seer the sole knower and inner Self.","The Cloud of Unknowing directs thought and will away from creatures toward God through naked intent.","The model predicts that traditions train a post-negation custody rule, not only a doctrine of self or no-self."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Udana 1.10, Bahiya Sutta, Thanissaro translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/KN/Ud/ud1_10.html","Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, https://www.brhat.in/openlibrary/special/brihadaranyaka-upanishad/3-7-23"],"structural_observation":"The primary contrast is real but narrower than the proposed model. Udana 1.10 uses the same seeing, hearing, sensing, cognizing sequence and then removes locatable self-reference. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 uses seeing, hearing, perceiving, knowing to identify the sole inner ruler and Self. This supports a strong no-owner versus hidden-seer contrast. The Christian leg is less exact: The Cloud of Unknowing chapter 3 begins with love and intent toward God, rather than first freeing neutral attention and then assigning it. Pseudo-Dionysius further strains the model because Mystical Theology chapter 5 places the Cause beyond both affirmation and negation, so even God as a stable recipient is apophatically unstable. Cloud source: https://sacred-texts.com/chr/cou/cou08.htm. Dionysius source: https://hekhal.org/texts/mystical-theology-dionysius/","secondary_literature_gap":"I did not find the exact phrase or structure of attention custody across Buddhist no-self, Advaita witness, and Christian apophatic prayer. However, close prior work already distinguishes common mystical experience, culturally shaped interpretation, monistic versus theistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and pure awareness. The originality is therefore a reframing of a known comparison around practice-level ownership language, not a standalone discovery.","risk_of_overread":"High. The term attention imports modern psychology into texts that speak about clinging, Self, inner ruler, will, love, and God. Bahiya may be about ending clinging rather than leaving attention unowned. Brihadaranyaka may be ontological rather than attentional. The Cloud may intensify desire rather than suspend ownership."},"literature_search_queries":["objectless awareness Advaita Buddhist Christian apophatic","pure consciousness event Forman Advaita Buddhism Christian mysticism objectless","attention Cloud of Unknowing Bahiya Atman","Fasching I Am of the Nature of Seeing witness-consciousness Buddhist Advaita","pure awareness experience Ramm 2023 witness consciousness selfless","minimal phenomenal experience objectless selfless awareness Buddhist Advaita"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, sections on union, apophatic mysticism, perennialism, Stace, Smart, and Zaehner, https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/mysticism/","overlap":"Already distinguishes Advaita identity with Brahman, theistic union or communion with God, Buddhist unconstructed experience, apophatic negation, and common-core versus constructivist interpretations.","difference":"It sorts experiences and doctrines, not the handoff of loosened attention or ownership permissions in practice.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The new model is close to a practice-language recoding of established mystical-experience typologies."},{"source":"Robert K. C. Forman, Mysticism, Mind, Consciousness, Google Books page, https://books.google.com/books/about/Mysticism_Mind_Consciousness.html?id=I28wCczdcpEC","overlap":"Forman's pure consciousness event and dualistic mystical state compare objectless or nonintentional awareness across Indian, Chinese, medieval European, and modern accounts.","difference":"Forman tends to argue for direct encounter with consciousness itself, while this idea emphasizes divergent custodians of attention after ordinary ownership weakens.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. Forman already frames the central terrain as contentless consciousness plus interpretive difference."},{"source":"Wolfgang Fasching, I Am of the Nature of Seeing: Phenomenological Reflections on the Indian Notion of Witness-Consciousness, PhilPapers, https://philpapers.org/rec/FASIAO-5","overlap":"Gives a close Advaita account of witness-consciousness as the abiding dimension in which changing experiences appear, directly overlapping the hidden-seer custody leg.","difference":"Does not triangulate with Bahiya's no-location instruction or Christian apophatic love.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction. One major unit of the model is already well articulated."},{"source":"Brentyn J. Ramm, Pure Awareness Experience, PhilPapers, https://philpapers.org/rec/RAMPAE-5","overlap":"Examines meditative reports of awareness itself and the possibility of non-sensory phenomenal character, close to the model's post-object attention zone.","difference":"Does not classify traditions by where freed attention may belong.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction. It covers the phenomenological base, but not the custody typology."},{"source":"Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html","overlap":"Shows apophatic language turning back on its own propositions and names across Greek, Christian, and Islamic texts, close to the Christian unknowing side.","difference":"Sells analyzes apophatic discourse and its paradoxes, not attention ownership across Buddhist, Advaita, and Christian practices.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction. It makes the Christian leg less new and highlights the Dionysian anomaly."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike common-core or constructivist accounts, this idea says the decisive variable is not only whether an experience is the same or differently interpreted, but whether training assigns loosened attention to no owner, the witnessing Self, or God.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Dzogchen or Mahamudra luminous selfless awareness, plus Pseudo-Dionysius's claim that the divine Cause is beyond both affirmation and negation.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"Luminous selfless awareness can look neither ownerless in a simple Bahiya sense, nor owned by an Atman, nor addressed to a devotional recipient. Dionysius also makes the Christian recipient unstable, because the final move refuses both affirmation and denial of God as a graspable object of intent.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence and pushes the idea away from candidate discovery toward extended synthesis."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Practitioners trained in Bahiya-style sense instruction, Advaita self-inquiry, and Christian apophatic prayer should diverge most in ownership and recipient language at the moment ordinary self-reference drops.","expected_observation":"Interview transcripts should cluster around no one there, witnessing Self, and God or beloved as recipient, even when sensory content and quietness descriptions overlap.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Reports cluster only by phenomenological texture, emotional tone, or teacher charisma, with no stable ownership or recipient pattern.","test_surface":"Micro-phenomenological interviews with trained Theravada, Advaita, and apophatic practitioners."},{"if_model_is_right":"Changing the instruction at the handoff point should change later interpretation more than immediate perceptual content.","expected_observation":"A practitioner given no-location language, witness language, or God-directed language after similar objectless calm should later describe different belonging or authorization, while reporting similar quiet or contentlessness.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"The initial phenomenology changes before doctrinal instruction, or the ownership language remains random after instruction.","test_surface":"Controlled meditation instruction study with post-session interview coding."},{"if_model_is_right":"Primary manuals should contain explicit or implicit custody rules near passages that loosen ordinary selfing.","expected_observation":"Texts should pair negation of objects or self-story with instructions such as do not locate a self, know the unseen seer, or lift the heart to God.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"The relevant manuals loosen objects without any subsequent owner, Self, or recipient language, or use all three interchangeably.","test_surface":"Close-reading corpus of Theravada, Advaita, Christian apophatic, Dzogchen, and Mahamudra manuals."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Theravada insight teachers familiar with Bahiya and sense restraint","Advaita Vedanta self-inquiry teachers","Christian apophatic contemplative directors","Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers","Scholars of mysticism and contemplative science"],"questions":["When object fixation and ordinary self-story weaken, where does your practice tell attention or awareness to rest, belong, or not belong?","Is the word custody obvious, useful, or misleading from inside your tradition?","Would changing the handoff instruction change realization, only later interpretation, or neither?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners say this is just the standard experience versus interpretation debate, or say attention is the wrong category and the model misses liberation, ontology, grace, or devotion.","answers_that_support_contribution":"Practitioners independently identify a decisive handoff point and report that no-owner, witness, and God-directed instructions change practice understanding."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Psychotherapy and secular attention training","structural_translation":"De-identification practices loosen ordinary ownership of thoughts, then assign the released stance to no-self mindfulness, observing self, values, therapist relationship, or a higher power.","prediction":"Programs with similar decentering exercises should diverge in outcomes and language according to the post-decentering recipient they train.","would_count_against_it":"If de-identification outcomes and reports are unaffected by ownership or recipient framing, the custody structure is probably only a theological gloss."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.68,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.58,"source_reliability":0.76,"counterargument_quality":0.88},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.72 to about 0.58. The custody phrase appears fresh, but the structure sits close to established work on pure consciousness, constructivism, theistic versus monistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and apophasis.","next_loop_instructions":["Close-read Dzogchen and Mahamudra instructions on rigpa or luminous awareness against Bahiya and Brihadaranyaka before publishing the custody model.","Code practitioner reports for ownership terms, recipient terms, and no-location terms instead of general contentless-awareness terms.","Search Zaehner, Stace, Ninian Smart, Forman, Katz, Pike, McGinn, and Sells before raising novelty above extended.","Ask a Christian apophatic practitioner whether love toward God is a recipient of freed attention or the starting motive of the whole practice."]},{"idea_id":"75a5718aa9a991ec","agent":"claude","title":"The Method's Reckoning: What a Practice Does With Its Own Authority at Completion","exact_claim":"At completion, contemplative methods face a self-authority question: some confirm themselves, some cancel themselves, and some dissolve the practitioner beyond method-talk, with consequences for verification and transmission.","claim_units":["A method's relation to its own result may be a comparative variable upstream of doctrinal content.","Mandukya is classified as self-confirming because analysis of waking, dreaming, and deep sleep culminates in turiya as Atman to be known.","Nagarjuna, Heart Sutra, Zen koan, and Eckhart are classified as self-canceling because their tools undermine graspable thesis, wisdom, attainment, or desire.","Zhuangzi, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana are classified as self-dissolving because the practitioner or frame of method becomes irrelevant.","The type should predict verification architecture, teaching strategy, and ethical consequences."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Mandukya Upanishad verse 7, Sanskrit and translation, https://texts.wara.in/upanishads/mukhya/mandukya/ and https://gita.pub/upanishad/mandukya/verse/7/","Heart Sutra, Sanskrit and English, https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/प्रज्ञापारमिताहृदय and https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Shorter_Prajñāpāramitā_Hṛdaya_Sūtra"],"structural_observation":"The Mandukya and Heart Sutra contrast is promising but not clean. Mandukya verse 7 negates ordinary consciousness categories, then ends by saying this is Atman and is to be known, which supports a confirming limit move. Yet Shankara's commentary also says affirmative and negative language fail, so Mandukya contains a self-canceling linguistic element. The Heart Sutra negates aggregates, sense bases, ignorance, the four truths, wisdom, and attainment, which supports the self-canceling reading. Yet it immediately says bodhisattvas rely on Prajnaparamita and gives a mantra, so the method is retained as reliance and recitation, not simply canceled. The close read supports a two-axis model better than a pure three-box typology.","secondary_literature_gap":"I did not find an exact three-type typology of contemplative methods as confirming, canceling, and dissolving at completion. But the self-canceling portion has very strong prior art in Nagarjuna, Wittgenstein ladder readings, Buddhist raft discussions, and Sells on apophatic unsaying. The dissolving portion is also standard in fana, zuowang, and Dzogchen descriptions. The new part is the comparative axis and its predicted consequences, not the individual patterns.","risk_of_overread":"High. The model imposes a modern reflexive category, method's relation to itself, on traditions that may speak instead of upaya, realization, grace, direct recognition, non-grasping, or annihilation of ego. It also risks treating stage-specific pedagogies as stable types."},"literature_search_queries":["self-dismantling methods Nagarjuna Wittgenstein therapy liberation","self-canceling method mysticism apophasis Nagarjuna Eckhart","therapeutic Nagarjuna Wittgenstein Tractatus ladder","Mystical Languages of Unsaying meaning event","method cancels itself dissolves contemplative practice","spiritual method abandon raft Upanishad Heart Sutra comparison","Victor Hori Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum koan practice curriculum","Zhuangzi fish trap words meaning forget words text"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/id/eprint/80007/","overlap":"Very close to the self-canceling core: Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein are read as shared philosophical method without theses, aimed at dissolution of philosophical problems and soteriological disquiet.","difference":"Bilateral comparison only. It does not add self-confirming and self-dissolving alternatives or predict verification architecture across traditions.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The strongest part of the Lumenary claim, method succeeds by undoing its own authority, is already explicit prior art."},{"source":"Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html","overlap":"Apophatic discourse is described as repeatedly turning back upon its own propositions and names, across Greek, Christian, and Islamic texts including Eckhart and Ibn Arabi.","difference":"Sells studies apophatic language as discourse, not a general typology of contemplative method completion.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for Eckhart and apophasis. Moderate support for the broader synthesis."},{"source":"MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, Thanissaro translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN22.html","overlap":"The Dhamma is a raft for crossing, to be grasped properly and then let go. This is a direct prior structure for validated-then-abandoned method.","difference":"It is not simply canceling or dissolving. It validates proper use, then releases attachment after the crossing.","novelty_impact":"High reduction and major anomaly. It suggests a fourth pattern or a two-axis framework."},{"source":"Jan Westerhoff, The No-Thesis View: Making Sense of Verse 29 of Nagarjuna's Vigrahavyavartani, PhilPapers PDF, https://philpapers.org/archive/WESTNV.pdf","overlap":"Closely analyzes Nagarjuna's no-thesis claim and the problem of how a work full of arguments can deny having theses.","difference":"The focus is semantic and argumentative context, not contemplative practice types or cross-tradition transmission.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the Nagarjuna unit, but it also sharpens the audit by warning against treating no-thesis as simple self-cancellation."},{"source":"G. Victor Sogen Hori, Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum, search-accessible copy, https://docslib.org/doc/1302437/the-koan-is-said-to-pose-to-the-ze-n-practitione-r-a-parado-x-unsolvabl-e-by-the-rational-intellectualizing-mind","overlap":"Directly addresses the common model of koan using reason to drive itself into self-contradiction, then complicates it by describing a curriculum after kensho.","difference":"It shows that a self-canceling tool can become a highly structured authorization system, contrary to a simple prediction of transmission difficulty.","novelty_impact":"High reduction and anomaly for the Zen evidence."},{"source":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, discussion of fana and baqa, https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/mysticism/","overlap":"Already describes Sufi fana as passing away of self followed by being filled with Allah's presence, close to the dissolving pattern.","difference":"It does not make fana one member of a cross-method typology.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction. The dissolving example is known, but the comparative placement may remain useful."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on apophatic unsaying, or the raft and ladder motifs, this idea proposes a three-way comparative axis and claims that the axis predicts verification and transmission better than doctrine alone.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Validated-then-abandoned hybrids, especially MN 22's raft, Heart Sutra reliance on Prajnaparamita after no-attainment, and Rinzai koan curriculum after kensho.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"These cases mix confirmation, cancellation, and dissolution across stages. The raft must be grasped properly before being released. The Heart Sutra negates attainment but retains reliance and mantra. Koan practice may exhaust conceptual striving yet becomes a formal curriculum with tests. If hybrids are normal, the three types are not stable categories.","confidence_effect":"Substantially lowers confidence in the three-box typology. The contribution survives better as a two-axis or staged model."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Method-type should predict verification architecture better than tradition membership.","expected_observation":"Eckhart and Nagarjuna should share more indirect, anti-possessive verification patterns with each other than Eckhart shares with more kataphatic Christian mystics. Advaita witness practice should use more direct recognition language than Madhyamaka critique.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Christian sources cluster together by tradition more strongly than by method-type, or all traditions use the same teacher, lineage, and conduct criteria regardless of method relation.","test_surface":"Coded comparison of practice manuals, teacher testing language, and post-realization instructions across at least six traditions."},{"if_model_is_right":"Dual-trained practitioners should report different relations to their own insight when switching method-types.","expected_observation":"After Advaita inquiry, practitioners describe recognition as stable witness or Self. After Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice, they resist treating any insight as an attained object. After Dzogchen or fana language, they emphasize effortless presence or transformed embodiment over method success.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Practitioners report no stable difference, or differences track teacher personality and institutional context more than method-type.","test_surface":"Structured interviews with practitioners trained in more than one contemplative lineage."},{"if_model_is_right":"Hybrid traditions should show explicit boundary management between method stages.","expected_observation":"Texts should mark when to use, trust, undermine, release, or embody a method. Examples would include raft language, preliminary versus main practice, koan curriculum before and after kensho, or thorn-removing-thorn metaphors.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"No boundary markers appear, or methods freely confirm, cancel, and dissolve without any pedagogical distinction.","test_surface":"Historical and textual analysis of Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, Madhyamaka, Sufi, and Christian apophatic training sequences."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Rinzai Zen teachers familiar with koan curriculum","Madhyamaka scholars and monastic teachers","Advaita Vedanta self-inquiry teachers","Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers","Sufi teachers familiar with fana and baqa","Christian apophatic spiritual directors"],"questions":["At completion, can the method still authorize its result, or must it be released, denied, or embodied?","Is confirming, canceling, dissolving an obvious distinction from inside your training, or does it distort the practice?","Do your verification methods change depending on whether the practice confirms, cancels, or dissolves itself?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners say every serious path already uses all three stages, or identify the model as a familiar upaya, raft, ladder, no-thesis, fana, or Gelassenheit pattern with new labels.","answers_that_support_contribution":"Practitioners find that the type distinction clarifies why different lineages test realization, authorize teachers, and warn against grasping insight in different ways."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Psychotherapy, education, and research methods","structural_translation":"Some methods confirm themselves by producing stable results, some cancel themselves by dissolving the problem frame, and some dissolve into skilled embodiment where the practitioner no longer follows the method explicitly.","prediction":"Methods that cancel their own frame should rely more on supervision, case judgment, paradox, and indirect signs than on checklist fidelity. Methods that confirm themselves should tolerate manuals and outcome criteria better. Methods that dissolve into embodiment should prioritize apprenticeship and exemplars.","would_count_against_it":"If confirmation, cancellation, and dissolution do not predict training, verification, or institutional form outside contemplative traditions, the proposed structure may be domain-specific rhetoric."},"originality_status":"novel_synthesis","confidence":0.74,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.64,"source_reliability":0.78,"counterargument_quality":0.91},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.84 to about 0.64. No exact three-type typology was found in accessible searches, but the self-canceling and method-abandoning structures are well-known, and primary texts show hybrid cases that weaken the clean typology.","next_loop_instructions":["Rebuild the model as two axes: validates versus undermines, and retained versus abandoned or embodied.","Close-read Mandukya, Heart Sutra, MN 22, Vigrahavyavartani 29, and Hori's koan curriculum before treating the three types as stable.","Search further for upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removes-thorn, Gelassenheit, fana and baqa, rang grol, and practice-realization as exact structural near-neighbors.","Ask dual-trained practitioners whether the typology changes how they understand transmission, or whether it merely renames standard stage pedagogy."]}]}
